{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "COOxidation",
        "description": "CO oxidation chemistry diagnostics from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Ch. 6 В§6.3 Eqs. 6.9-6.18, pp. 212-219. CO oxidation is the simplest hydrocarbon-oxidation mechanism and illustrates the catalytic HOx cycling that drives tropospheric ozone production (net: CO + 2Oв‚‚ + hОЅ в†’ COв‚‚ + Oв‚ѓ, with OH regenerated through HOв‚‚ + NO). This observed-only algebraic component implements six diagnostic relations: the OH loss rate L_OH (to CO, NOв‚‚, Oв‚ѓ), the HOв‚‚ loss rate L_HO2 (to NO, the HOв‚‚ self-reaction, and Oв‚ѓ), the HOx radical-termination loss rate L_HOx (OH+NOв‚‚в†’HNOв‚ѓ plus the HOв‚‚ self-reaction), the high-NOx HOв‚‚ steady-state concentration HO2_ss (Eq. 6.18), the net ozone production rate P_O3 (HOв‚‚+NO production minus the OH+Oв‚ѓ and HOв‚‚+Oв‚ѓ loss channels), and the HOx chain length (propagation rate over termination rate вЂ” the number of OH-HOв‚‚ cycles before radical termination). Observed-only algebraic system (no time derivatives): twelve variables (six inputs CO/OH/HOв‚‚/NO/NOв‚‚/Oв‚ѓ encoded as parameters, six outputs L_OH/L_HO2/L_HOx/HO2_ss/P_O3/chain_length as state), six rate-constant parameters (k_CO_OH, k_HO2_NO, k_HO2_HO2, k_OH_NO2, k_HO2_O3, k_OH_O3), one dimensionless stoichiometric constant (two), and six algebraic equations. Migrated from GasChem.jl@8c12c048 src/co_oxidation.jl:88 (`COOxidation` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "co-oxidation",
            "hox-cycling",
            "ozone-production",
            "tropospheric-chemistry",
            "observed-only",
            "seinfeld-pandis"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-kzix)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 6 В§6.3, Eqs. 6.9-6.18, pp. 212-219. CO oxidation as the simplest hydrocarbon-oxidation mechanism: the HOx catalytic cycle (CO + OH в†’ COв‚‚ + H; H + Oв‚‚ + M в†’ HOв‚‚ + M; HOв‚‚ + NO в†’ OH + NOв‚‚; NOв‚‚ + hОЅ в†’ NO + O; O + Oв‚‚ + M в†’ Oв‚ѓ + M), the HOв‚‚ steady state, the HOx chain length, and net ozone production. Rate constants from Table B.1."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "COOxidation": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/co_oxidation.jl:88\n\nUpstream `COOxidation` is an MTK `@component` with 12 `@variables` (6 inputs CO/OH/HOв‚‚/NO/NOв‚‚/Oв‚ѓ + 6 outputs P_O3/L_HOx/L_OH/L_HO2/chain_length/HO2_ss), 6 `@parameters` (k_CO_OH, k_HO2_NO, k_HO2_HO2, k_OH_NO2, k_HO2_O3, k_OH_O3), 1 `@constants` (two), and 6 algebraic equations from S&P Ch. 6 В§6.3 Eqs. 6.9-6.18. The upstream test compiles the system with `compile_with_inputs(sys, [:CO, :OH, :HO2, :NO, :NO2, :O3])` and solves it as a `NonlinearProblem` with the six inputs pinned to user-supplied concentrations.\n\nVariable-classification convention: the six input @variables (CO, OH, HOв‚‚, NO, NOв‚‚, Oв‚ѓ) are encoded here as `type: parameter` because they have no defining equation within the COOxidation component itself вЂ” they are externally-supplied inputs that the upstream compile treats via `compile_with_inputs(...)` (i.e. `mtkcompile` with `inputs=[...]`). This mirrors the rig-wide convention applied by sibling ope.esm (its five input @variables OH/HOв‚‚/ROв‚‚/NO/NOв‚‚ are encoded as `type: parameter`) and oh_production.esm/stefan_boltzmann.esm/typical.esm. The six output @variables (L_OH, L_HO2, L_HOx, HO2_ss, P_O3, chain_length) are encoded as `type: state` because each has exactly one defining algebraic equation. The single upstream `@constants` entry `two` (the stoichiometric factor 2 for the HOв‚‚ self-reaction HOв‚‚ + HOв‚‚ в†’ Hв‚‚Oв‚‚ + Oв‚‚, which consumes two HOв‚‚ radicals per event) is preserved verbatim as `type: parameter` with a fixed default of 2.0 вЂ” mirroring the constantв†’parameter convention of sibling oh_production.esm (`two`), chapman.esm, gwp.esm and stefan_boltzmann.esm: encoding it as a named dimensionless parameter lets MTK's unit checker treat it as a named quantity rather than a magic literal in the L_HO2 and L_HOx right-hand sides, and lets downstream consumers override the stoichiometric factor for sensitivity studies. The upstream structural test `COOxidation: Structural Verification` (test/test_co_oxidation.jl:4-32) asserts `length(unknowns(sys)) == 12`, `length(equations(sys)) == 6`, and `length(parameters(sys)) == 7` вЂ” the .esm preserves this with the 12 declared @variable entries (6 type:parameter inputs + 6 type:state outputs), 6 entries in `equations`, and 7 declared parameter entries (the 6 rate constants + the `two` constant; MTK counts `@constants` in `parameters(sys)`, hence 7, not 6).\n\nRate-constant CGSв†’SI translation: the upstream Julia declares the six rate constants as the SI-converted CGS values via explicit multiplication by 1e-6 (the cmВі/molec/s в†’ mВі/s factor for bimolecular rate coefficients):\n  k_CO_OH   = 2.4e-13 В· 1.0e-6 = 2.4e-19 mВі/s   (CO + OH в†’ COв‚‚ + H, S&P В§6.3 R6.9 вЂ” the chain-initiating CO-consumption step)\n  k_HO2_NO  = 8.1e-12 В· 1.0e-6 = 8.1e-18 mВі/s   (HOв‚‚ + NO в†’ OH + NOв‚‚, R6.11 вЂ” the Oв‚ѓ-producing chain-propagation step that regenerates OH)\n  k_HO2_HO2 = 2.9e-12 В· 1.0e-6 = 2.9e-18 mВі/s   (HOв‚‚ + HOв‚‚ в†’ Hв‚‚Oв‚‚ + Oв‚‚, R6.15 вЂ” the low-NOx HOx self-termination)\n  k_OH_NO2  = 1.0e-11 В· 1.0e-6 = 1.0e-17 mВі/s   (OH + NOв‚‚ + M в†’ HNOв‚ѓ, R6.12 вЂ” the high-NOx HOx/NOx termination)\n  k_HO2_O3  = 2.0e-15 В· 1.0e-6 = 2.0e-21 mВі/s   (HOв‚‚ + Oв‚ѓ в†’ OH + 2Oв‚‚ вЂ” an Oв‚ѓ-loss channel)\n  k_OH_O3   = 7.3e-14 В· 1.0e-6 = 7.3e-20 mВі/s   (OH + Oв‚ѓ в†’ HOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ вЂ” an Oв‚ѓ-loss channel)\nThe .esm encodes the clean SI literals 2.4e-19, 8.1e-18, 2.9e-18, 1.0e-17, 2.0e-21, 7.3e-20 directly вЂ” matching the SI-literal convention of sibling ope.esm and oh_production.esm. Three of the six literals are bit-identical to the upstream Julia product (k_HO2_NO 8.1e-18, k_HO2_HO2 2.9e-18, k_OH_O3 7.3e-20); the other three differ from the product by exactly one ULP (k_CO_OH 2.4e-19 vs the product 2.3999999999999997e-19, k_OH_NO2 1.0e-17 vs 9.999999999999999e-18, k_HO2_O3 2.0e-21 vs 2.0000000000000002e-21 вЂ” each a ~1e-16 relative difference). Every inline-test expected value below is computed from the .esm's own declared literal defaults, so the file is internally exact at the rel=1e-10 inline-test tolerance regardless of that choice; the 1-ULP literal-vs-product difference is ~6 orders of magnitude below rel=1e-10 and far below the upstream tests' own rtol=0.01-0.05 acceptance bounds.\n\nObservability classification: this component is purely algebraic вЂ” every output variable is the LHS of one algebraic equation in the inputs, parameters, and (for chain_length) another output. No equation contains a `D(В·)` operator, so the `(t)` time index has no role and the trajectory is constant in time. Test and example scenarios use `time_span: [0.0, 1.0]` and sample at t=0, mirroring the convention used by sibling observed-only ESM files (ope.esm, oh_production.esm, gwp.esm).\n\nEquation cascade: the six equations form a topologically-ordered cascade вЂ” L_OH, L_HO2, L_HOx, HO2_ss and P_O3 depend only on inputs and parameters; chain_length depends on the output L_HOx. chain_length's equation is written `chain_length ~ (k_HO2_NOВ·HO2В·NO) / L_HOx` (referencing the L_HOx output variable) rather than fully inlined вЂ” this preserves the upstream symbolic structure (S&P writes the HOx chain length as a propagation rate divided by a termination rate) instead of the fully-expanded form, mirroring the ope.esm / oh_production.esm cascade convention. Equation order in the `equations` array follows the upstream `eqs` array verbatim (L_OH, L_HO2, L_HOx, HO2_ss, P_O3, chain_length); since L_HOx precedes chain_length the order is already a valid topological sort.\n\nNumerical defaults: the upstream input @variables carry no defaults вЂ” the .esm defaults are taken from the canonical upstream test scenario shared by the four `COOxidation` equation-verification tests (`Eq 6.18 HO2 Steady-State`, `Net O3 Production Rate`, `HOx Loss Rate`, `Chain Length`, test/test_co_oxidation.jl:60-192), all in SI mвЃ»Ві:\n  CO  = 2.5e18 mвЃ»Ві  (~100 ppb at STP air number density 2.5e25 mвЃ»Ві)\n  OH  = 1.0e12 mвЃ»Ві  (~1e6 molec/cmВі, typical daytime tropospheric OH)\n  HOв‚‚ = 1.0e14 mвЃ»Ві  (~1e8 molec/cmВі, typical daytime tropospheric HOв‚‚)\n  NO  = 2.5e15 mвЃ»Ві  (~0.1 ppb at STP)\n  NOв‚‚ = 2.5e16 mвЃ»Ві  (~1 ppb at STP)\n  Oв‚ѓ  = 1.0e18 mвЃ»Ві  (~40 ppb at STP, typical tropospheric ozone)\nAt these defaults: L_OH = 9.23e11, L_HO2 = 2.283e12, L_HOx = 3.08e11, P_O3 = 1.752e12 mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№, HO2_ss = 2.963e13 mвЃ»Ві, chain_length = 6.575 (dimensionless).\n\nUpstream test reproduction:\n- `COOxidation: Structural Verification` (test_co_oxidation.jl:4-32) вЂ” reproduced by the .esm structural shape (12 @variable entries = 6 parameter + 6 state, 6 equations, 7 parameter entries).\n- `COOxidation: Rate Constants at 298 K` (test_co_oxidation.jl:197-211, asserts the six k_* defaults) вЂ” reproduced implicitly by the declared rate-constant defaults; `upstream_defaults_all_outputs` pins all six outputs, each computed from the rate constants, so any wrong default shifts a pinned value.\n- `COOxidation: Eq 6.18 HO2 Steady-State (High NOx)` (test_co_oxidation.jl:60-93, upstream rtol=0.05 on HO2_ssв‰€2.963e13) вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `upstream_defaults_all_outputs` at rel=1e-10.\n- `COOxidation: Net O3 Production Rate` (test_co_oxidation.jl:95-126, upstream rtol=0.01 on P_O3в‰€1.752e12) вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `upstream_defaults_all_outputs`.\n- `COOxidation: HOx Loss Rate` (test_co_oxidation.jl:128-158, upstream rtol=0.01 on L_HOxв‰€3.08e11) вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `upstream_defaults_all_outputs`.\n- `COOxidation: Chain Length` (test_co_oxidation.jl:160-192, upstream rtol=0.02 on chain_lengthв‰€6.58, bounded 1 < chain_length < 100) вЂ” reproduced and tightened by `upstream_defaults_all_outputs`.\n- `COOxidation: HOx Catalytic Cycling` (test_co_oxidation.jl:368-395, asserts chain_length > 1 and P_O3 > 0 at defaults) вЂ” reproduced by `upstream_defaults_all_outputs` (pins chain_length=6.575 > 1 and P_O3=1.752e12 > 0).\n- `COOxidation: High NOx - Short Chain Length` (test_co_oxidation.jl:272-303, asserts L_HOx(high NOx) > L_HOx(low NOx) and chain_length > 0 for both) вЂ” reproduced by the pair `upstream_high_nox_short_chain_low_nox` / `upstream_high_nox_short_chain_high_nox`, which pin both endpoints at rel=1e-10 (L_HOx 1.395e11 < 3.7645e12; both chain lengths positive вЂ” the upstream cross-test inequality becomes a structural fact under the two pinned values).\n- `COOxidation: Qualitative - Positive Production and Loss` (test_co_oxidation.jl:337-366, sweeps OHГ—HOв‚‚Г—NO over a 3Г—3Г—3 grid and asserts L_OH/L_HO2/L_HOx/HO2_ss all > 0) вЂ” reproduced by `upstream_qualitative_low_corner` and `upstream_qualitative_high_corner`, the two extreme corners of that grid, which pin all four (positive) loss/steady-state outputs at rel=1e-10.\nThe remaining tests extend coverage beyond the upstream suite: term isolation by zeroing Oв‚ѓ / CO / HOв‚‚, single-input doubling of OH / NO / NOв‚‚ / CO / Oв‚ѓ, the low-NOx long-chain and high-NOx short-chain regimes, the HOв‚‚-self-reaction-dominated termination regime, and a `two`-constant override sentinel.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-10 / abs=1.0e-12): the six algebraic equations are small expression trees вЂ” the largest (L_OH, L_HO2) sum three 3-factor products (в‰¤11 IEEE-754 ops); HO2_ss and chain_length each add one division; P_O3 subtracts two products from a third. Each output is correctly-rounded to within a few ULP в‰€ 1e-15 relative; rel=1e-10 leaves ~5 orders of magnitude of headroom and is far tighter than the upstream rtol=0.01-0.05. The abs=1.0e-12 floor gates the exact-IEEE-754-zero outputs that arise at the term-isolation boundaries (HO2_ss=0 when CO=0; L_HO2=0 and chain_length=0 when HOв‚‚=0), catching the stuck-at-non-zero failure mode. Matches sibling observed-only ESM tolerance: ope.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12, oh_production.esm rel=1e-10/abs=1e-12.\n\nUnit balance (verified): all six equations balance dimensionally.\n  L_OH  `k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH + k_OH_NO2В·OHВ·NO2 + k_OH_O3В·OHВ·O3`: each term (mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»Ві)В·(mвЃ»Ві) = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ вњ“\n  L_HO2 `k_HO2_NOВ·HO2В·NO + twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·HO2ВІ + k_HO2_O3В·HO2В·O3`: (mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»Ві)В·(mвЃ»Ві) and (1)В·(mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»вЃ¶) = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ вњ“\n  L_HOx `k_OH_NO2В·OHВ·NO2 + twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·HO2ВІ`: (mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»Ві)В·(mвЃ»Ві) and (1)В·(mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»вЃ¶) = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ вњ“\n  HO2_ss `k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH / (k_HO2_NOВ·NO)`: (mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№)/(sвЃ»В№) = mвЃ»Ві вњ“\n  P_O3  `k_HO2_NOВ·HO2В·NO в€’ k_OH_O3В·OHВ·O3 в€’ k_HO2_O3В·HO2В·O3`: each term (mВі/s)В·(mвЃ»Ві)В·(mвЃ»Ві) = mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ вњ“\n  chain_length `k_HO2_NOВ·HO2В·NO / L_HOx`: (mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№)/(mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№) = dimensionless вњ“\nAll concentrations in SI mвЃ»Ві, rate constants in SI mВі/s, production/loss rates in mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№, chain length dimensionless. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-10,
                "abs": 1.0e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "two": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 2.0,
                    "description": "Stoichiometric factor for the HOв‚‚ self-reaction HOв‚‚ + HOв‚‚ в†’ Hв‚‚Oв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ (S&P В§6.3 R6.15): two HOв‚‚ radicals are consumed per reaction event, so the HOx loss contributed by the self-reaction is twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·[HOв‚‚]ВІ. Upstream this is an MTK `@constants` entry (default 2, dimensionless); it is preserved here as `type: parameter` with a fixed default of 2.0 so MTK's unit checker sees a named dimensionless quantity rather than a magic literal in the L_HO2 and L_HOx right-hand sides, and so downstream consumers can override the stoichiometric factor for sensitivity studies. The `two_constant_override_sentinel` test overrides it to 1.0 to catch a regression that hard-codes the factor as a literal."
                },
                "k_CO_OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 2.4e-19,
                    "description": "CO + OH в†’ COв‚‚ + H rate constant (S&P В§6.3 R6.9, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.4e-19 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.4e-13 cmВі/molec/s. This is the chain-initiating step of the CO-oxidation cycle вЂ” it consumes CO and an OH radical, producing the H atom that promptly forms HOв‚‚. k_CO_OH appears in the OH loss rate L_OH and (via the COВ·OH product) in the high-NOx HOв‚‚ steady state HO2_ss. The clean literal 2.4e-19 differs from the upstream Julia product 2.4e-13В·1.0e-6 = 2.3999999999999997e-19 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                },
                "k_HO2_NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 8.1e-18,
                    "description": "HOв‚‚ + NO в†’ OH + NOв‚‚ rate constant (S&P В§6.3 R6.11, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 8.1e-18 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 8.1e-12 cmВі/molec/s. This is the Oв‚ѓ-producing chain-propagation step: it regenerates OH (sustaining the catalytic HOx cycle) and converts NO to NOв‚‚, whose subsequent photolysis yields an Oв‚ѓ molecule. k_HO2_NO appears in the HOв‚‚ loss rate L_HO2, the gross Oв‚ѓ-production term of P_O3, the HOв‚‚ steady-state denominator HO2_ss, and the chain_length numerator. The clean literal 8.1e-18 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 8.1e-12В·1.0e-6."
                },
                "k_HO2_HO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 2.9e-18,
                    "description": "HOв‚‚ + HOв‚‚ в†’ Hв‚‚Oв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ rate constant (S&P В§6.3 R6.15, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.9e-18 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.9e-12 cmВі/molec/s. This is the dominant HOx self-termination channel at low NOx вЂ” the HOв‚‚ self-reaction that converts two HOв‚‚ radicals into stable hydrogen peroxide. It enters the HOв‚‚ loss rate L_HO2 and the HOx loss rate L_HOx as the quadratic term twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·[HOв‚‚]ВІ (the factor `two` for the two-HOв‚‚-per-event stoichiometry). The clean literal 2.9e-18 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 2.9e-12В·1.0e-6."
                },
                "k_OH_NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 1.0e-17,
                    "description": "OH + NOв‚‚ + M в†’ HNOв‚ѓ rate constant (S&P В§6.3 R6.12, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 1.0e-17 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 1.0e-11 cmВі/molec/s. This termolecular reaction is the dominant daytime HOx/NOx termination at high NOx: it removes an OH radical and an NOв‚‚ molecule, converting reactive nitrogen into nitric acid. It enters the OH loss rate L_OH and the HOx loss rate L_HOx. The clean literal 1.0e-17 differs from the upstream Julia product 1.0e-11В·1.0e-6 = 9.999999999999999e-18 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                },
                "k_HO2_O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 2.0e-21,
                    "description": "HOв‚‚ + Oв‚ѓ в†’ OH + 2Oв‚‚ rate constant (S&P В§6.3, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 2.0e-21 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 2.0e-15 cmВі/molec/s. This is a slow ozone-loss channel вЂ” HOв‚‚ reacting directly with ozone вЂ” that subtracts from net Oв‚ѓ production P_O3 and adds to the HOв‚‚ loss rate L_HO2. The clean literal 2.0e-21 differs from the upstream Julia product 2.0e-15В·1.0e-6 = 2.0000000000000002e-21 by exactly one ULP (see model reference notes)."
                },
                "k_OH_O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^3/s",
                    "default": 7.3e-20,
                    "description": "OH + Oв‚ѓ в†’ HOв‚‚ + Oв‚‚ rate constant (S&P В§6.3, Table B.1, 298 K). The upstream default 7.3e-20 mВі/s is the SI-converted form of the CGS value 7.3e-14 cmВі/molec/s. This ozone-loss channel вЂ” OH reacting with ozone вЂ” subtracts from net Oв‚ѓ production P_O3 and adds to the OH loss rate L_OH. The clean literal 7.3e-20 is bit-identical to the upstream Julia product 7.3e-14В·1.0e-6."
                },
                "CO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e18,
                    "description": "Carbon monoxide number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 2.5e18 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 100 ppb at STP air number density (2.5e25 mвЃ»Ві) and matches the canonical upstream test scenario (test_co_oxidation.jl:65). CO is the oxidized substrate of the cycle вЂ” it appears in the OH loss term k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH of L_OH and (via the COВ·OH product) in the HOв‚‚ steady state HO2_ss. Encoded as `type: parameter` because COOxidation has no governing equation for CO вЂ” it is purely an input, set via `parameter_overrides` in tests and `parameter_sweep` in examples."
                },
                "OH": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1.0e12,
                    "description": "Hydroxyl radical number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input from the coupled HOx chemistry). The default 1.0e12 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 1e6 molec/cmВі is the typical daytime tropospheric OH concentration and matches the canonical upstream test scenario. OH appears in all three terms of the OH loss rate L_OH, in the OH+NOв‚‚ term of the HOx loss rate L_HOx, in the OH+Oв‚ѓ loss term of P_O3, and in the HOв‚‚ steady state HO2_ss. Encoded as `type: parameter` (externally-supplied input with no governing equation in this component)."
                },
                "HO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1.0e14,
                    "description": "Hydroperoxyl radical number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 1.0e14 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 1e8 molec/cmВі is the typical daytime tropospheric HOв‚‚ concentration and matches the canonical upstream test scenario. HOв‚‚ appears in all three terms of the HOв‚‚ loss rate L_HO2 (linearly in the HOв‚‚+NO and HOв‚‚+Oв‚ѓ terms, quadratically in the self-reaction term), in the quadratic self-reaction term of L_HOx, and linearly in the gross-production and HOв‚‚+Oв‚ѓ-loss terms of P_O3 and in the chain_length numerator. Encoded as `type: parameter`."
                },
                "NO": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e15,
                    "description": "Nitric oxide number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 2.5e15 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 0.1 ppb at STP and matches the canonical upstream test scenario. NO drives the Oв‚ѓ-producing HOв‚‚+NO chain-propagation step: it appears in the HOв‚‚+NO term of L_HO2, the gross-production term of P_O3, the chain_length numerator, and (in the denominator) the HOв‚‚ steady state HO2_ss. Encoded as `type: parameter`. Note: HO2_ss = k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH / (k_HO2_NOВ·NO) divides by NO, so NO must remain strictly positive вЂ” the inline tests keep NO в‰Ґ 1e14 mвЃ»Ві."
                },
                "NO2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 2.5e16,
                    "description": "Nitrogen dioxide number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 2.5e16 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 1 ppb at STP and matches the canonical upstream test scenario (NO/NOв‚‚ ratio 0.1, the canonical daytime photostationary partitioning). NOв‚‚ appears in the OH+NOв‚‚ termination term of both the OH loss rate L_OH and the HOx loss rate L_HOx вЂ” so raising NOв‚‚ shortens the HOx chain. Encoded as `type: parameter`."
                },
                "O3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1.0e18,
                    "description": "Ozone number density [mвЃ»Ві] (externally-supplied input). The default 1.0e18 mвЃ»Ві в‰€ 40 ppb at STP is a typical tropospheric ozone concentration and matches the canonical upstream test scenario. Oв‚ѓ appears in the OH+Oв‚ѓ loss term of L_OH, the HOв‚‚+Oв‚ѓ loss term of L_HO2, and both ozone-loss terms subtracted in the net Oв‚ѓ production rate P_O3. Encoded as `type: parameter`."
                },
                "P_O3": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "Net ozone production rate [mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№] (S&P В§6.3, Eqs. 6.9-6.13): P_O3 = k_HO2_NOВ·HOв‚‚В·NO в€’ k_OH_O3В·OHВ·Oв‚ѓ в€’ k_HO2_O3В·HOв‚‚В·Oв‚ѓ. The gross production term k_HO2_NOВ·HOв‚‚В·NO counts the Oв‚ѓ molecules made via HOв‚‚ + NO в†’ OH + NOв‚‚ followed by NOв‚‚ photolysis; the two subtracted terms are the OH+Oв‚ѓ and HOв‚‚+Oв‚ѓ ozone-loss channels. At the default scenario P_O3 в‰€ 1.752e12 mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№ (net positive вЂ” production dominates). P_O3 can go negative when NO is too low to drive much production while Oв‚ѓ is high (see `upstream_qualitative_low_corner`) or when HOв‚‚ vanishes so only the OH+Oв‚ѓ loss term survives (see `zero_ho2_net_o3_destruction`)."
                },
                "L_HOx": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "HOx radical-termination loss rate [mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№] (S&P В§6.3, Eqs. 6.11-6.12): L_HOx = k_OH_NO2В·OHВ·NOв‚‚ + twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·HOв‚‚ВІ. The two radical-termination channels вЂ” OH + NOв‚‚ + M в†’ HNOв‚ѓ (the high-NOx NHL channel) and the HOв‚‚ + HOв‚‚ в†’ Hв‚‚Oв‚‚ self-reaction (the low-NOx HHL channel, carrying the stoichiometric factor `two`). At the default scenario L_HOx в‰€ 3.08e11 mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№. L_HOx is the denominator of the HOx chain length: a smaller L_HOx (low NOx, low HOв‚‚) gives a longer catalytic chain."
                },
                "L_OH": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "OH radical loss rate [mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№] (S&P В§6.3, Eq. 6.17 denominator): L_OH = k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH + k_OH_NO2В·OHВ·NOв‚‚ + k_OH_O3В·OHВ·Oв‚ѓ вЂ” the total rate at which OH is consumed by reaction with CO, with NOв‚‚, and with Oв‚ѓ. At the default scenario L_OH в‰€ 9.23e11 mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№. Linear in OH; the OH+CO channel dominates at the default CO=2.5e18 (~100 ppb) loading."
                },
                "L_HO2": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3*s^-1",
                    "description": "HOв‚‚ radical loss rate [mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№] (S&P В§6.3): L_HO2 = k_HO2_NOВ·HOв‚‚В·NO + twoВ·k_HO2_HO2В·HOв‚‚ВІ + k_HO2_O3В·HOв‚‚В·Oв‚ѓ вЂ” the total rate at which HOв‚‚ is consumed by reaction with NO, by the HOв‚‚ self-reaction (with the stoichiometric factor `two`), and by reaction with Oв‚ѓ. At the default scenario L_HO2 в‰€ 2.283e12 mвЃ»ВіВ·sвЃ»В№, dominated by the HOв‚‚+NO chain-propagation channel. Quadratic in HOв‚‚ through the self-reaction term, linear in HOв‚‚ through the other two."
                },
                "chain_length": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "HOx chain length [dimensionless] (S&P В§6.3): chain_length = (k_HO2_NOВ·HOв‚‚В·NO) / L_HOx вЂ” the propagation rate of the Oв‚ѓ-producing HOв‚‚ + NO step divided by the HOx termination rate, i.e. the number of OH-HOв‚‚ catalytic cycles a HOx radical completes before it is terminated. The equation references the L_HOx output variable rather than inlining its expression, preserving the upstream symbolic structure. At the default scenario chain_length в‰€ 6.575 (a HOx radical drives ~6-7 Oв‚ѓ-producing cycles before termination). chain_length > 1 confirms genuine catalytic cycling; it rises in the low-NOx long-chain regime and falls below 1 in the high-NOx short-chain regime."
                },
                "HO2_ss": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "HOв‚‚ steady-state concentration in the high-NOx limit [mвЃ»Ві] (S&P В§6.3 Eq. 6.18): HO2_ss = k_CO_OHВ·COВ·OH / (k_HO2_NOВ·NO). At high NOx, HOв‚‚ is removed primarily by reaction with NO, so the steady-state HOв‚‚ balances its production from the CO + OH в†’ ... в†’ HOв‚‚ initiation against the HOв‚‚ + NO loss. At the default scenario HO2_ss в‰€ 2.963e13 mвЃ»Ві. Proportional to CO and OH, inversely proportional to NO; it is a diagnostic estimate independent of the actual HOв‚‚ input used elsewhere in the component."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "L_OH",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_CO_OH", "CO", "OH"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_OH_NO2", "OH", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_OH_O3", "OH", "O3"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "L_HO2",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_NO", "HO2", "NO"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["two", "k_HO2_HO2", {"op": "^", "args": ["HO2", 2]}]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_O3", "HO2", "O3"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "L_HOx",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_OH_NO2", "OH", "NO2"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["two", "k_HO2_HO2", {"op": "^", "args": ["HO2", 2]}]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "HO2_ss",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_CO_OH", "CO", "OH"]},
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_NO", "NO"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "P_O3",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "-",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_NO", "HO2", "NO"]},
                                    {"op": "*", "args": ["k_OH_O3", "OH", "O3"]}
                                ]
                            },
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_O3", "HO2", "O3"]}
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "lhs": "chain_length",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {"op": "*", "args": ["k_HO2_NO", "HO2", "NO"]},
                            "L_HOx"
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_defaults_all_outputs",
                    "description": "Reproduces and tightens the four upstream `COOxidation` equation-verification tests at the canonical default scenario (every input and rate constant at its declared default: CO=2.5e18, OH=1e12, HOв‚‚=1e14, NO=2.5e15, NOв‚‚=2.5e16, Oв‚ѓ=1e18 mвЃ»Ві). The upstream `Eq 6.18 HO2 Steady-State` test (test_co_oxidation.jl:60-93) asserts HO2_ssв‰€2.963e13 at rtol=0.05; `Net O3 Production Rate` (95-126) asserts P_O3в‰€1.752e12 at rtol=0.01; `HOx Loss Rate` (128-158) asserts L_HOxв‰€3.08e11 at rtol=0.01; `Chain Length` (160-192) asserts chain_lengthв‰€6.58 at rtol=0.02 with 1 < chain_length < 100; `HOx Catalytic Cycling` (368-395) asserts chain_length>1 and P_O3>0. This test pins all six outputs at rel=1e-10 вЂ” up to 8 orders of magnitude tighter than the upstream bounds. Because nothing is overridden it also implicitly reproduces the upstream `Rate Constants at 298 K` test (197-211): any wrong rate-constant default would shift a pinned output off its value.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "L_OH", "time": 0.0, "expected": 923000000000.0001},
                        {"variable": "L_HO2", "time": 0.0, "expected": 2283000000000.0},
                        {"variable": "L_HOx", "time": 0.0, "expected": 308000000000.0},
                        {"variable": "HO2_ss", "time": 0.0, "expected": 29629629629629.633},
                        {"variable": "P_O3", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1752000000000.0},
                        {"variable": "chain_length", "time": 0.0, "expected": 6.574675324675325}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_high_nox_short_chain_low_nox",
                    "description": "Low-NOx endpoint of the upstream `COOxidation: High NOx - Short Chain Length` test (test_co_oxidation.jl:272-303). Inputs CO=2.5e18, OH=5.0e11, HOв‚‚=5.0e13, NO=2.5e15, NOв‚‚=2.5e16, Oв‚ѓ=1e18 mвЃ»Ві вЂ” the radical pool halved from the default. Pins all six outputs at rel=1e-10. Pairs with `upstream_high_nox_short_chain_high_nox` to reproduce the upstream cross-test assertion L_HOx(high NOx) > L_HOx(low NOx): this endpoint pins L_HOx=1.395e11, the high-NOx endpoint pins L_HOx=3.7645e12, so the inequality holds structurally. chain_length=7.258 > 0 satisfies the upstream positivity assertion.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"OH": 5.0e11, "HO2": 5.0e13},
                    "time_span": {"start": 0.0, "end": 1.0},
                    "assertions": [
                        {"variable": "L_OH", "time": 0.0, "expected": 461500000000.00006},
                        {"variable": "L_HO2", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1127000000000.0},
                        {"variable": "L_HOx", "time": 0.0, "expected": 139500000000.0},
                        {"variable": "HO2_ss", "time": 0.0, "expected": 14814814814814.816},
                        {"variable": "P_O3", "time": 0.0, "expected": 876000000000.0},
                        {"variable": "chain_length", "time": 0.0, "expected": 7.258064516129032}
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upstream_high_nox_short_chain_high_nox",
                    "description": "High-NOx endpoint of the upstream `COOxidation: High NOx - Short Chain Length` test (test_co_oxidation.jl:272-303). Same halved radical pool (OH=5.0e11, HOв‚‚=5.0e13) but NO=2.5e17 and NOв‚‚=7.5e17 mвЃ»Ві вЂ” two orders of magnitude more NOx. Pins all six outputs at rel=1e-10. L_HOx=3.7645e12 here far exceeds the low-NOx endpoint's 1.395e11, reproducing the upstream L_HOx-grows-with-NOx assertion as a structural fact; chain_length=26.9 > 0. (At this high-NOx point the chain length is longer than at the low-NOx endpoint because the gross-propagation numerator k_HO2_NOВ·HOв‚‚В·NO scales with NO вЂ” up 100Г— вЂ” faster than the NOв‚‚-driven OH+NOв‚‚ termination term; the upstream test asserts only chain_length > 0, not a chain-length ordering.)",
                    "parameter_overrides": {"OH": 5.0e11, "HO2": 5.0e13, "NO": 2.5e17, "NO2": 7.5e17},
